I used to love this place but I have not been there for a while and now I had the most awful experience so I have to share it. We ordered $150 worth of food. When delivery arrived the guacamole was missing. Instead of complaining I just went to the restaurant and kindly showed them my order and asked them for the missing guac. I simply assumed it is no big deal and they will either provide a refund or just hand me the dish. Instead they said write down your information and we will send a free guac next time you order. I patiently explained that this is not the way to handle it and if this is how they want to go about it, I probably won't be ordering from them any more. They simply did not care for the fact that I paid $10 for a guac that they never provided. And they did not feel like it was their obligation to make it right. So instead of dealing with this kind of attitude ever again, I am taking my future business elsewhere.  Mistakes do happen, what matters is how you handle it. And  to my amazement the manager was just nasty about it.

A year ago, my husband and I married and held the ceremony at El Mariachi in the private rooms. We've been back several times since. Just a few days ago, we celebrated our first anniversary and had a small group from our wedding party join us to celebrate. With so much turmoil and uneasiness in these COVID times, El Mariachi could supply a dose of familiarity and normalcy. Our group was larger than the standard maximum of 6, so the restaurant got us two six-tops next to each other, which still allowed us to converse.  Luis was the man who helped out with every step of the way when we planned our wedding, and he was there during our anniversary dinner. He was around to talk with us for a bit, pour some champagne, and even had someone show up to take pictures! It was so delightful! He filled us in on a Day of the Dead tequila dinner happening in a few weeks, and it sounds fantastic. We ordered a few pitchers of margaritas because we believe they are the best around, and could probably win a margarita competition now that I think about it.  El Mariachi has been so lovely to us. When we didn't know what appetizers or food to order, the server (Julio) was able to help us out. He was patient when we were silly and couldn't focus. They were able to bring the food out altogether, which was nice. They didn't rush us out immediately after 90 minutes, and they allowed us to take our time and chat after our meal. We were there in the later dinner hours, so that helped. It didn't look like anyone was waiting for our tables.  El Mariachi continues to treat us like family and serve delicious margaritas and food. We ordered churros for dessert, and I thought my husband would die of tasty food overload. They were so delicious. We will continue going back to the restaurant when we get the chance. Thank you!

El Mariachi is a mixed bag of goods... Here is my take  The food: High quality!  So the food here is very good (with the he exception of the salsa). The flavors are great the presentation is beautiful and the quality of ingredients is fantastic.  Now is this authentic Mexican? No, but it has enough of those iconic flavors to give you a great eating experience that's pretty close to what Mexican cuisine is.  Are the portions big? No, and this is where things start going down hill. The portions are very small considering how expensive this food is, and it is very expensive.  Price: $40 per person including appetizers and and drinks and before tip.  Now you might be thinking, " Hey that's not that bad. It's pretty standard for the area." Well, not exactly. There are plenty of places where you can get high quality Mexican for a fraction of the price without compromising on the portions.  Eating here makes you realize you might be playing more for the building lease than the actual food.  Drinks: This is where I lost all respect.  They had special margarita pitchers, which might have been the worst margaritas I have ever had.  If I could describe them I would say they are watered down, Minute Maid powder mix margaritas with some random tequila mixed in.  No sense of presentation. No sense of quality or freshness... I have had cheaper and better.  The service:  In terms of service this restaurant is actually doing something right. The staff is very patient and friendly. They made the experience worth the wait.  I will note that they started cleaning and picking up the chairs all around us which made it feel like they wanted us out.  This is disappointing, specially since we were barely eating. And they did not come back to offer more drinks which made it feel like they might have wanted us out.  Ambiance:  The place is decent sized. Not big but not small. It's clean and the decor is cute. Bathrooms were very clean which is always a plus.  Bottom line:  This place has very good food and good service for me though the prices do not meet the portions and the drinks don't come to the level the food is at which is a huge deal breaker.  I wouldn't mind coming here if invited but would probably not pick it on my own because I feel there are better alternatives. Having said that, of you do come here I feel you would have a decent time... as long as you are not here near closing, in which case you might notice them putting up the chairs around you to give you a hint to wrap it up.

I came here with my cousins for brunch but didn't do the mimosa package. We were more interested in their margaritas and cocktail menu. They did not disappoint. Our favorite was the smoked pineapple margarita. You can taste the smokiness of the drink. It was delicious. We also had the platanos French toast. It was a bit too sweet for my liking but still good! We had their complimentary flan and it was huge and yummy. Our server was amazing! She was friendly, assertive and welcoming. Would come back to try their mimosa brunch package!

I loved the enchiladas with maduros (sweet plantains) as well as the veggie fajitas.  Highly recommend! The bar area is also great if you are just dining solo.

El Mariachi is a gem, with outstanding good, exceptional service, and a comfortable atmosphere. The sampler platter of appetizers is great for sharing, a offers a sense of the quality this restaurant offers. Yet here, even the homemade tortilla chips taste like some of the best Mexican food. It is like visiting some of the restaurants in San Antonio. As to the main dishes, the meat, fish, and chicken dishes offer fine choices. Plus, the vegetarian items are worth ordering. The Aztecs combo represents the vegetarian choices well, and the shrimp burrito In the Del Ranchero combo has wo detful nuance  In fact, the various combo plates include several parts of the menu that are worth exploring on repeat visits. With staff like Anita, you are in great hands here. If you have not yet tried it, you should plan a visit. It is one of the best Mexican restaurants in the area.
